                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d269">
                <head>269. Memorandum of a Conversation Between the Canadian Ambassador (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RNA1" type="from">Robertson</persName>) and the Acting Assistant
                    Secretary of State for Economic Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_AWC1" type="to"
                        >Armstrong</persName>), Ambassador’s Residence, Washington, July 24,
                        1957<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d269fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Central Files, 411.006/7–2457. Confidential. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_AWC1">Armstrong</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1957-07-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 24, 1957</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Cabinet Committee Report on Crude Oil Imports</item>
                </list>
                <p>In the course of a lunch at the home of the Canadian Ambassador, I had occasion
                    to inform him generally of the nature of the Cabinet Committee report on crude
                    oil imports.<note n="2" xml:id="d269fn2">
                        <ref target="#d270">
                            <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> He expressed great satisfaction with the way in which the
                    formula would operate, and with the fact that no practical limitation on
                    Canadian oil was being proposed.</p>
            </div>
